+# Choose the Discourse extension boundary
+
+Use the lowest row that fully satisfies the requirement.
+
+| Mechanism | Use for | Keep out |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| Site setting/core feature | behavior Discourse already supports | brand-only reinvention |
+| Theme CSS variables/SCSS | tokens, typography, spacing, responsive presentation | new data or permissions |
+| Existing official theme component | maintained reusable behavior with strong coverage | heavy forks to force a poor fit |
+| Transformer/modifier/public theme API | supported changes to data or rendering contracts | undocumented internals |
+| Plugin outlet + internal `.gjs` | theme-owned markup and client interaction | server persistence or authorization |
+| Separate custom theme component | independently reusable/deployable client feature | one-off page styling |
+| Plugin | server data, endpoints, jobs, permissions, persistence | visual-only work |
+| Core contribution | broadly useful capability agreed with Discourse | project-specific branding |
+
+## Theme versus theme component
+
+Keep work in the parent theme when it implements the approved brand and page language and ships only with that theme. Create a separate theme component when the feature has its own settings, release lifecycle, reusable behavior, and value across multiple themes.
+
+An internal `.gjs` file is a component in the programming sense; it does not need to become a separately installable Discourse theme component.
+
+## Escalation triggers
+
+Request approval before:
+
+- installing or forking a third-party theme component;
+- creating a new separately deployed theme component;
+- creating a plugin or changing server behavior;
+- modifying or patching Discourse core;
+- using `modifyClass`, a template replacement, direct DOM mutation, or undocumented internals;
+- hiding native controls or changing permission-dependent behavior;
+- adopting an experimental API.
+
+## Blocks API caution
+
+Discourse described a new Blocks API in its June 26, 2026 current-projects update and stated that it was still changing. Treat it as experimental until current official documentation and the Discourse team confirm a stable contract for the target version. Do not put it in the production path based only on an announcement.
+
+Source: [Discourse current projects, June 2026](https://meta.discourse.org/t/current-projects-june-2026/406097).
+
+## Decision record
+
+Record substantial choices in `docs/EXTENSION_DECISIONS.md` if the repository uses that document:
+
+| Requirement | Options checked | Chosen boundary | Why | Version/evidence | Owner | Revisit trigger |
+| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
+
+Include the Discourse team's answer when a contract has been confirmed directly.
