+# Implement and test in the Discourse style
+
+Use the target repository and target Discourse version as the source of truth. The examples below are architectural guidance, not permission to invent APIs.
+
+## Theme structure
+
+Preserve the established tree. A modern theme commonly contains:
+
+```text
+about.json
+settings.yml
+locales/
+common/common.scss
+stylesheets/
+javascripts/discourse/api-initializers/*.gjs
+spec/system/
+.discourse-compatibility
+```
+
+Keep entry files small. Organize SCSS by the existing convention, such as foundation/tokens, components, and surfaces. Use BEM-like classes for theme-owned markup. Style native Discourse selectors directly only when the selector is stable and narrowly scoped.
+
+## CSS and responsive rules
+
+- Reuse core CSS custom properties before creating project tokens.
+- Put Hercules brand values behind `--hercules-*` tokens when working in the Hercules repository.
+- Use shallow selectors and a route or theme-owned block as the scope.
+- Use logical properties where they improve RTL support.
+- Use the Discourse viewport library when available:
+
+```scss
+@use "lib/viewport";
+
+.hercules-card {
+  @include viewport.until(md) {
+    // Mobile/tablet adaptation
+  }
+}
+```
+
+- Avoid fixed page heights, hard-coded multi-column widths, global resets, and broad `!important`.
+
+## Client customization
+
+Use `.gjs` for modern Glimmer components and co-located templates. Initialize theme behavior with `apiInitializer`. Prefer supported APIs in this order:
+
+1. settings and modifiers;
+2. transformers;
+3. plugin outlets;
+4. documented theme API methods;
+5. narrowly scoped compatibility fallback.
+
+The official guides show current patterns:
+
+- [Using outlets to insert and replace content](https://meta.discourse.org/t/theme-developer-tutorial-4-using-outlets-to-insert-and-replace-content/357799)
+- [Customizing the topic list with transformers](https://meta.discourse.org/t/customizing-the-topic-list/350411)
+- [Discourse theme authoring skill](https://github.com/discourse/discourse-theme-skills/tree/main/.claude/skills/discourse-theme-authoring)
+
+Verify API names in the target source before code generation. Do not use deprecated `.hbs` template overrides for new work.
+
+## Settings, locales, and compatibility
+
+- Put administrator-tunable behavior in `settings.yml`.
+- Put all user-visible text in locale files and use theme translation helpers.
+- Add settings only when a real administrator choice exists; do not turn every design token into a setting.
+- Declare the compatible Discourse range when relying on version-specific APIs.
+- Document any release-channel assumption.
+
+## Tests
+
+Run the repository's own commands. Do not guess package scripts. At minimum:
+
+- lint and format changed SCSS/JS/GJS/YAML;
+- execute existing theme unit/system tests;
+- add a system spec for new user-visible behavior or interaction;
+- use `core_features` pages when the theme relies on native routes and fixtures;
+- test settings on/off and permission-sensitive states;
+- check the browser console for errors and deprecation warnings.
+
+Official reference: [End-to-end system testing for themes and theme components](https://meta.discourse.org/t/end-to-end-system-testing-for-themes-and-theme-components/281579).
+
+## Visual and accessibility review
+
+Capture matching viewport screenshots for the design and implementation. Verify:
+
+- keyboard order, visible focus, semantic controls, and accessible names;
+- hover, focus, active, disabled, loading, empty, error, and overflow states;
+- zoom and long translated strings;
+- mobile and touch targets;
+- configured color schemes and contrast;
+- behavior with native content variations and enabled theme components.
+
+Do not approve a visual diff by hiding content, fixing sample text widths, or replacing native behavior solely to match one static frame.
